Comment_contributor: The number kwandap ‘one’ appears to derive from the determiner kwan ‘a(n), some, (an)other’
alternatively, the form inin may be an iconic reduplication of in
The form in may be a simple haplology of inin
The word for ‘five’ is, quite transparently ipï ‘hand’ plus kwandap ‘one’ (i.e. ‘one hand’), a clear indication of the hand-counting system that underlies the quinary numerical system.
‘hand one one 3sg.obj=atop be-ipfv’ (i.e. ‘one hand, one is atop it’)
Pondi speakers can refer to multiples of ten by using the form yalïme, which may derive from yalïm ‘ironwood tree’.

Value: yalïme ipï kwandap kwandap mat pï
yalïme ipï kwandap inin mat pï
yalïme ipï kwandap yawle mat pï
yalïme ipï kwandap nanïnge mat pï
